===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|bal}}, {{m|enm|ball}}, {{m|enm|balle}}, from {{inh|en|ang|*beall}}, {{m|ang|*bealla||round object, ball}} or {{der|en|non|bǫllr||a ball}}, both from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*balluz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*ballô||ball}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰoln-||bubble}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰel-||to blow, inflate, swell}}. Cognate with {{cog|osx|ball}}, {{cog|nl|bal}}, {{cog|goh|bal}}, {{m|goh|ballo}} ({{cog|de|Ball||ball}}; {{m|de|Ballen||bale}}). Related forms in Romance are borrowings from Germanic. See also {{l|en|balloon}}, {{l|en|bale}}.
